There is a cultural transition that happens in 1956-57, when many major rock and roll pioneers debut: Buddy Holly, Elvis, Carl Perkins, and Little Richard.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
1950: First half of the year had a lot of good time fun novelty hits like Rag Mop and Music Music Music. The Korean War started in the summer and then most of the hits are maudlin tunes like Harbor Lights and Mona Lisa. Since the industry was just transitioning to tape, you still hear a lot of records with that damp direct-to-disc sound.
1951: As see previous. Most hits are slow and droopy outside of How High The Moon, which is kind of proto rock and roll. The Tennessee Waltz is the mega hit and is covered by multiple artists.
1952: A pretty bland year without many notable songs other than two horrible monuments to Mitch Miller schlock (Shrimp Boats and You Belong To Me).
1953: Yet more dull songs. The most well-known major hit of this year was the infamous How Much Is That Doggie In The Window
1954: Aside from several pieces of infamous schlock like Oh Mein Papa and That's Amore, this is the first year where doo-wop and rock-and-roll begins to reach the Billboard. There's a general trend towards faster, more punchy pop now that the Korean War was over and America was in an optimistic mood.
1955: As everyone knows, year zero for rock-and-roll. Singing girl groups are a fad this year with the De Castro Sisters, Chordettes, Fontane Sisters, McGuire Sisters, and one hit wonder De John Sisters all logging major hits. Established pop singers and groups doing R&B covers is also all over the charts.
1956: The year Elvis explodes. The Billboard year end was 60% rock and roll and doo-wop compared to 30% for '55, marking the definitive takeover of the new generation.
1957: Peak rock and roll with pre-rock pop acts being increasingly marginalized on the charts
1958: With the first half of the year being still R&R dominated, this comes to a gradual halt in the summer and a year and a half of safe blandness starts to settle in.
1959: Most hits are slow or mid-tempo doo-wop or light pop. Lots of reverb vocals everywhere.

Let me outline it:
1950-1956: traditional pop
1956-1958/59/60: rock n roll appears (American dominated)
1958/59/60-1963: Brill building pop- danceable, orchestral-based pop with rock influence. At the same time Brits have reorganized what remained of the rock n roll wave
1963-1966: British invasion ("post-rocknroll", one could say)
1965/66: folk rock
1967: psychedelia

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
Find an old second hand dual turntable or something well made but inexpensive, get a cheap phono preamp, and a cheap made in china amp, or get a yamaha amp with at least 75w of power and tone control (avoid graphic eq) get a vintage pair of kef like a c30 or C15 speakers, or find a decent pair of second hand polks, or some second hand klipsch bookshelves (for at least %60 off street price) … go to your local record store pull out everything remotely interesting from their dollar bin, check for warps, and bad scratches, spend about 30min needle dropping stuff at the listening station,

This is how i buy 20 albums every week and only spend like $25

Also dont buy expensive speaker cables, buy wire cutters instead, you can also use scissors, just cut the cable off am old lamp - all you need is a good gauge wire

Listening on LP that's amped correctly into bookshelf speakers is excellent
The thing with vinyl is that its best appreciated while on shrooms or LSD because the soundstage and imaging expand such that you literally just start hearing things that aren't there and enjoying something you've never heard before
other than that, there's nothing that vinyl provides that FLAC's played through a good PMP, good DAC, with good IEMs won't also give you
this is especially true considering most modern music is recorded and passed through an ADC to be digitized
You could argue that the ideal way to reproduce modern music is specifically NOT to listen to it on vinyl because you're at the mercy of whatever DAC was used to mix and press the sound into the vinyl, and you're better off converting it with a DAC that suits the music and your ears better

Frankly, that's part of why Magma is by far my favorite zeuhl act, and not just because they were my first one. Haven't listened to Bondage Fruit yet, but I'm familiar with the other three bands you listed and like them a lot, but the chaos and energy they go for kinda misses out on that more otherworldy celestial vibe that Magma typically goes for. I think part of it is that they mostly hone in on the prog and rock elements, but most of Magma is very consciously informed by Carl Orff and John Coltrane, which is part of what makes zeuhl "Zeuhl" in the first place. I guess it's kinda ironic that the progenitors of this subgenre are actually the least accessible to some prog fans.
And just to warn you, their albums from 2004 and onwards after their reunion only get less "prog rock" sounding. The electric guitar becomes more of an afterthought, and a bigger emphasis is placed on the vocal harmonies.

>What do u mean by this?
He's not talking about microphone distance or any production stuff. Projecting your voice is basically making it louder while also making it fuller and more clear. Imagine the way you would talk if you had to give an hour long lecture to a room of 100 people with no microphone. You would be loud and clear but you wouldn't strain or scream because then your voice would blow out in a few minutes. To do that you would breathe and elevate in a certain way, and that's projection. That's something that's necessary to sing well. You've already got a naturally good voice so you're at an advantage. When you learn through time and muscle memory to be in tune, you will already have a great sound going, even without proper projection. But when you learn projection, you will have a greater range of expressions, tones, and dynamics that will give you the freedom to sing whatever you want. There are artists who used very little projection, like Nick Drake, and they had a certain sound because of it. Not that it's a bad thing, but it is more limited. Some people think limitations like that are good for creativity. But in my opinion, the kind of music you're doing has a wide range of possibilities, and it will be better for you if you can project. Unless you want to develop some kind of Johnny Cash sound, like Colter Wall is doing.

>>114015605
A compressor allows you to make the quiet parts of something louder, and the louder parts quiet - thereby "compressing" the final waveform.

Attack: How quickly the compressor starts to compress the audio. If it's very fast, the transients (very fast, sharp peaks) in things like snare drums and kick drums and vocals will be compressed [turned down] and potentially make the music sound less dynamic. Alternatively, if attack is very slow, the compressor won't be grabbing on to very much since it's just letting more loud sounds through.

Release: How quickly the compressor "lets go" of the signal it's compressing and starts looking for more audio to compress. The important thing to know about this is that if the release is very slow, the compressor is just turning down the audio and staying there. Fast release times tend to make things sound like they're "breathing" and are a major reason things might sound "compressed", whether that's good or bad is subjective.

Threshold: The audio level at which the compressor will actually kick in. Say you have an uncompressed snare drum that peaks around -12dB. If your compressor threshold is set anywhere above -12dB, the compressor will never engage because there's no audio it sees as loud enough to compress.

Ratio: The most convoluted setting to explain, probably the one that requires the most practical experience to understand. In my experience, ratios below 7:1 have essentially no impact on the audio unless you're trying to make reference-quality recordings. Basically, ratio is "how much" the compressor actually compresses the audio when it hits the threshold. The most useful model of compressor to demonstrate this is an 1176, or maybe a Distressor.

If you have access to it, the user interface for a Midas M32 or a Behringer X32 has a fantastic visual representation of a compressor that can help you understand these parameters.

What I'm trying to get at is the fact that human psychoacoustic processing doesn't give a shit what the meters on your compressor say, changes in volume of 2-3 decibels are getting into the realm of imperceptible for the average listener. It is meant to feel like an epic length album, with an overarching narrative, thematic chapters, different landscapes, moods and styles. It is a psychedelic experience. It moves through the four yugas, the dark night of the soul, paradise, .. the overall list moves through different times of day in a linear fashion. Every track has at least two qualities of some kind it shares with the prior track, creating a very seamless experience. It has many different angles of meaning as an overall experience, like the words in finnegans wake.
